  "prompt": "What are some of the lesser known but must-see places in Pune?",
  "response": "Pune, often seen as the cultural capital of Maharashtra, has a rich tapestry of history, culture, and natural beauty. While places like Shaniwar Wada and the Aga Khan Palace are renowned, there are several lesser-known but equally fascinating spots to explore:\n\n1. **Pataleshwar Cave Temple**: This 8th-century rock-cut cave temple dedicated to Shiva is a peaceful spot amid the city's hustle and bustle. The intricate carvings and monolithic structure are truly impressive.\n\n2. **Vetal Tekdi**: Also known as Vetal Hill, it is the highest point in Pune and offers panoramic views of the city. It's a great place for trekking, bird watching, and enjoying a quiet sunset.\n\n3. **Chaturshringi Temple**: Located on a hill, this temple dedicated to Goddess Chaturshringi is not only a spiritual destination but also offers a scenic view of the city.\n\n4. **Baneshwar Temple**: Situated a bit away from the city, this beautiful temple dedicated to Lord Shiva is surrounded by lush greenery and a natural spring, creating a serene atmosphere.\n\n5. **Kelkar Museum**: Raja Dinkar Kelkar Museum houses an impressive collection of artifacts showcasing 18th and 19th-century India. From musical instruments to textiles and household items, each exhibit has a story to tell.\n\n6. **Pu La Deshpande Garden**: Also known as the Pune-Okayama Friendship Garden, it offers a tranquil escape with its Japanese garden layout and beautifully landscaped spaces.\n\n7. **Sinhagad Fort**: This might be slightly more known, but it remains less crowded compared to other historical spots in Pune. The fort has significant historical importance and requires a trekking effort, offering stunning views, quaint food stalls, and historical intrigue.\n\n8. **Bhuleshwar Temple**: Located a bit outside Pune in the town of Malshiras, this 13th-century temple dedicated to Shiva is noteworthy for its unique architecture and intricate carvings.\n\n9. **Junnar Caves**: An hour\u2019s drive from Pune, these ancient rock-cut Buddhist caves are lesser explored but provide a deep dive into the historical and spiritual side of the region.\n\n10. **Pashan Lake**: This artificial lake offers a serene environment ideal for bird watching, jogging, and enjoying a peaceful afternoon by the water.\n\nEach of these destinations has its own unique charm and allows you to explore the diverse historical, cultural, and natural facets of Pune.",
